He was convicted in 2013 for breaching medical ethics when he was involved in the former apartheid government's chemical and biological warfare programme. He was accused of supplying and producing kidnapping drugs, suicide pills and arming mortars with teargas. The media called him when details of the secret programme emerged. Local media report that he has been working as a cardiologist in at least two facilities in the Western Cape Province. His employer, in response to the backlash, said it "cannot prohibit Health Professions Council of South Africa registered doctors, includingÂ  Basson, from practising unless they are prevented by law from doing so". --BBC--